---
import LessonLayout from '../layouts/LessonLayout.astro';
import CanvasDemo from '../components/CanvasDemo.astro';
---

<LessonLayout
  number={1}
  title="Basics"
  description="Drawing your first shapes with fillRect, strokeRect, and clearRect."
  prev={{ href: '/00-foundation', title: 'Foundation' }}
  next={{ href: '/02-paths', title: 'Paths & Shapes' }}
>

<p>In the <a href="../00-foundation">Foundation lesson</a> you learned what Canvas is, how the coordinate system works, and what the <code>ctx</code> object does. Now it's time to draw. This lesson covers the three rectangle methods — the simplest way to put shapes on screen — plus colors, draw order, and practical examples.</p>


<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->
<!-- SECTION 1 — fillRect                          -->
<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->

<h2>fillRect — Drawing Filled Rectangles</h2>

<p>The simplest drawing command is <code>fillRect(x, y, width, height)</code>. It fills a rectangle with the current <code>fillStyle</code> color.</p>

<div class="concept">
  <p><strong>fillRect parameters:</strong></p>
  <pre style="color: var(--accent); font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.4;">
    ctx.fillRect(x, y, width, height)
                 │  │    │       │
                 │  │    │       └── how tall (in pixels)
                 │  │    └────────── how wide (in pixels)
                 │  └─────────────── Y of the top-left corner
                 └────────────────── X of the top-left corner

    Example: ctx.fillRect(50, 30, 200, 100)

    (50,30) ─────────── 200px ──────────┐
       │                               │
      100px                            │
       │                               │
       └───────────────────────────────┘
                                 (250,130)
  </pre>
</div>

<CanvasDemo
  id="fill-rect"
  title="fillRect(x, y, width, height)"
  width={500}
  height={300}
  code={`
// First, set the fill color
ctx.fillStyle = '#58a6ff';
// Draw a rectangle at (50,50), 200 wide, 100 tall
ctx.fillRect(50, 50, 200, 100);

// Change color and draw another
ctx.fillStyle = '#f778ba';
ctx.fillRect(150, 100, 200, 100);

// Semi-transparent rectangle (the 0.6 means 60% opacity)
ctx.fillStyle = 'rgba(63, 185, 80, 0.6)';
ctx.fillRect(250, 50, 200, 150);

// Label the first rectangle
ctx.fillStyle = '#e6edf3';
ctx.font = '12px monospace';
ctx.fillText('fillRect(50, 50, 200, 100)', 55, 95);
  `}
/>

<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->
<!-- SECTION 2 — fillStyle color formats           -->
<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->

<h2>fillStyle — Color Formats Explained</h2>

<p>Before drawing, you set the color with <code>ctx.fillStyle</code>. Canvas accepts many color formats. Here are the most common ones:</p>

<CanvasDemo
  id="color-formats"
  title="Color Formats Visual Reference"
  width={500}
  height={350}
  code={`
var y = 20;
var swatchSize = 40;

// Helper: draw a color swatch with label
function swatch(color, label, description) {
  ctx.fillStyle = color;
  ctx.fillRect(20, y, swatchSize, swatchSize);
  ctx.strokeStyle = '#30363d';
  ctx.lineWidth = 1;
  ctx.strokeRect(20, y, swatchSize, swatchSize);

  ctx.fillStyle = '#e6edf3';
  ctx.font = 'bold 13px monospace';
  ctx.fillText(label, 75, y + 18);
  ctx.fillStyle = '#8b949e';
  ctx.font = '12px monospace';
  ctx.fillText(description, 75, y + 35);
  y += 55;
}

// Named colors
swatch('tomato', "'tomato'", 'Named color (140+ built-in names)');

// Hex (6-digit)
swatch('#58a6ff', "'#58a6ff'", 'Hex: #RRGGBB (most common on web)');

// Hex (3-digit shorthand)
swatch('#f0f', "'#f0f'", 'Hex shorthand: #RGB (same as #ff00ff)');

// RGB function
swatch('rgb(210, 153, 34)', "'rgb(210, 153, 34)'", 'RGB: values 0-255 for Red, Green, Blue');

// RGBA (with transparency)
swatch('rgba(88, 166, 255, 0.5)', "'rgba(88,166,255,0.5)'", 'RGBA: like RGB but with alpha (0=invisible, 1=solid)');

// HSL
swatch('hsl(280, 70%, 60%)', "'hsl(280, 70%, 60%)'", 'HSL: Hue (0-360), Saturation %, Lightness %');
  `}
/>

<div class="concept">
  <p><strong>Which format should I use?</strong> For beginners, <strong>named colors</strong> (like <code>'red'</code>, <code>'dodgerblue'</code>) are easiest. For precise control, use <strong>hex codes</strong> (<code>'#58a6ff'</code>). When you need transparency, use <strong>rgba</strong>. The <code>fillStyle</code> stays set until you change it — it's like dipping your brush in paint.</p>
</div>

<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->
<!-- SECTION 3 — strokeRect                        -->
<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->

<h2>strokeRect — Outlined Rectangles</h2>

<p><code>strokeRect(x, y, width, height)</code> draws just the <strong>outline</strong> of a rectangle, without filling the inside. You control the outline color with <code>strokeStyle</code> and thickness with <code>lineWidth</code>.</p>

<CanvasDemo
  id="stroke-rect"
  title="strokeRect with Different Line Widths"
  width={500}
  height={300}
  code={`
// Thin outline (2px)
ctx.strokeStyle = '#58a6ff';
ctx.lineWidth = 2;
ctx.strokeRect(30, 30, 120, 80);
ctx.fillStyle = '#8b949e';
ctx.font = '11px monospace';
ctx.fillText('lineWidth = 2', 40, 135);

// Medium outline (5px)
ctx.strokeStyle = '#f778ba';
ctx.lineWidth = 5;
ctx.strokeRect(180, 30, 120, 80);
ctx.fillStyle = '#8b949e';
ctx.fillText('lineWidth = 5', 190, 135);

// Thick outline (10px)
ctx.strokeStyle = '#3fb950';
ctx.lineWidth = 10;
ctx.strokeRect(330, 30, 120, 80);
ctx.fillStyle = '#8b949e';
ctx.fillText('lineWidth = 10', 340, 135);

// Dashed outline
ctx.strokeStyle = '#d29922';
ctx.lineWidth = 3;
ctx.setLineDash([10, 5]);
ctx.strokeRect(30, 170, 200, 80);
ctx.fillStyle = '#8b949e';
ctx.font = '11px monospace';
ctx.fillText('setLineDash([10, 5])', 40, 275);
ctx.setLineDash([]);

// Dotted outline
ctx.strokeStyle = '#bc8cff';
ctx.lineWidth = 3;
ctx.setLineDash([3, 6]);
ctx.strokeRect(260, 170, 200, 80);
ctx.fillStyle = '#8b949e';
ctx.fillText('setLineDash([3, 6])', 270, 275);
ctx.setLineDash([]);
  `}
/>

<div class="concept">
  <p><strong>How lineWidth works:</strong> The stroke is centered on the edge of the rectangle. A <code>lineWidth</code> of 10 means 5 pixels inside the edge and 5 pixels outside. This is why thick outlines can look like they're "growing" the rectangle.</p>
  <pre style="color: var(--accent); font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.4;">
    lineWidth = 10

       5px outside
    ──────████████████──────
          █          █
          █  inside  █    5px inside
          █          █
    ──────████████████──────
       5px outside

    The stroke sits ON the boundary line,
    half in, half out.
  </pre>
</div>

<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->
<!-- SECTION 4 — clearRect                        -->
<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->

<h2>clearRect — Erasing Pixels</h2>

<p><code>clearRect(x, y, width, height)</code> makes a rectangular area fully transparent — it erases whatever was drawn there. Think of it as a rectangular eraser.</p>

<CanvasDemo
  id="clear-rect"
  title="clearRect — Cutting Holes"
  width={500}
  height={300}
  code={`
// Fill the entire canvas with blue
ctx.fillStyle = '#58a6ff';
ctx.fillRect(0, 0, 500, 300);

// Cut rectangular holes to reveal the background
ctx.clearRect(50, 50, 100, 80);
ctx.clearRect(200, 100, 150, 100);
ctx.clearRect(380, 30, 80, 250);

// You can draw on top of cleared areas
ctx.fillStyle = '#f778ba';
ctx.fillRect(60, 60, 30, 30);

// Label
ctx.fillStyle = '#e6edf3';
ctx.font = '12px monospace';
ctx.fillText('cleared areas become transparent', 50, 290);
  `}
/>

<p>The most common use of <code>clearRect</code> is clearing the <strong>entire</strong> canvas before redrawing (for animation):</p>
<div class="concept">
  <pre style="color: var(--accent); font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.4;">
    // Clear everything:
    ctx.clearRect(0, 0, canvas.width, canvas.height);
  </pre>
</div>

<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->
<!-- SECTION 5 — Draw Order / Compositing         -->
<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->

<h2>Draw Order — What Happens When Shapes Overlap</h2>

<p>Canvas works like painting on paper with opaque paint: the last thing you draw covers everything before it. This is called <strong>painter's algorithm</strong> — just like a real painter, the newest layer goes on top.</p>

<CanvasDemo
  id="draw-order"
  title="Draw Order Matters!"
  width={500}
  height={300}
  code={`
// Draw three overlapping rectangles
// The ORDER you draw them determines what's on top

// First: red (drawn first = on the bottom)
ctx.fillStyle = '#f85149';
ctx.fillRect(50, 50, 180, 150);

// Second: green (covers part of red)
ctx.fillStyle = '#3fb950';
ctx.fillRect(130, 90, 180, 150);

// Third: blue (covers parts of both)
ctx.fillStyle = '#58a6ff';
ctx.fillRect(210, 40, 180, 150);

// Labels showing draw order
ctx.fillStyle = '#e6edf3';
ctx.font = 'bold 14px monospace';
ctx.fillText('1st', 120, 130);
ctx.fillText('2nd', 200, 175);
ctx.fillText('3rd', 280, 125);

// Explanation on the right
ctx.fillStyle = '#8b949e';
ctx.font = '12px monospace';
ctx.fillText('Drawn first', 410, 60);
ctx.fillText('= on bottom', 410, 78);
ctx.fillText('Drawn last', 410, 180);
ctx.fillText('= on top', 410, 198);
  `}
/>

<div class="concept">
  <p><strong>Key insight:</strong> Canvas has no "layers" and no "z-index." If you want shape A behind shape B, draw A first. If you want to change the order later, you have to clear the canvas and redraw everything in the new order. This is why animation always follows the pattern: <strong>clear -> draw everything -> repeat</strong>.</p>
</div>

<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->
<!-- SECTION 6 — Practical Example: Robot         -->
<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->

<h2>Practical Example: Drawing a Robot</h2>

<p>Let's use everything we've learned to draw something fun — a robot made entirely from rectangles!</p>

<CanvasDemo
  id="robot"
  title="Robot Made of Rectangles"
  width={500}
  height={400}
  code={`
// Background
ctx.fillStyle = '#0d1117';
ctx.fillRect(0, 0, 500, 400);

// ---- BODY ----
// Main body (torso)
ctx.fillStyle = '#30363d';
ctx.fillRect(190, 140, 120, 140);

// Head
ctx.fillStyle = '#30363d';
ctx.fillRect(200, 50, 100, 80);

// Antenna
ctx.fillStyle = '#8b949e';
ctx.fillRect(245, 20, 10, 30);
ctx.fillStyle = '#f85149';
ctx.fillRect(240, 10, 20, 15);

// Eyes
ctx.fillStyle = '#58a6ff';
ctx.fillRect(220, 70, 25, 20);  // left eye
ctx.fillRect(255, 70, 25, 20);  // right eye

// Pupils (small dark squares inside eyes)
ctx.fillStyle = '#0d1117';
ctx.fillRect(230, 75, 10, 10);
ctx.fillRect(262, 75, 10, 10);

// Mouth
ctx.fillStyle = '#3fb950';
ctx.fillRect(225, 105, 50, 8);

// Chest panel
ctx.fillStyle = '#21262d';
ctx.fillRect(210, 160, 80, 60);

// Chest lights
ctx.fillStyle = '#f85149';
ctx.fillRect(220, 170, 15, 15);
ctx.fillStyle = '#d29922';
ctx.fillRect(243, 170, 15, 15);
ctx.fillStyle = '#3fb950';
ctx.fillRect(266, 170, 15, 15);

// Arms
ctx.fillStyle = '#30363d';
ctx.fillRect(150, 150, 35, 100);  // left arm
ctx.fillRect(315, 150, 35, 100);  // right arm

// Hands
ctx.fillStyle = '#8b949e';
ctx.fillRect(155, 250, 25, 25);   // left hand
ctx.fillRect(320, 250, 25, 25);   // right hand

// Legs
ctx.fillStyle = '#30363d';
ctx.fillRect(205, 285, 35, 80);   // left leg
ctx.fillRect(260, 285, 35, 80);   // right leg

// Feet
ctx.fillStyle = '#8b949e';
ctx.fillRect(195, 365, 55, 20);   // left foot
ctx.fillRect(250, 365, 55, 20);   // right foot

// Ground shadow
ctx.fillStyle = 'rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3)';
ctx.fillRect(170, 385, 160, 10);
  `}
/>

<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->
<!-- SECTION 7 — Practical Example: House          -->
<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->

<h2>Practical Example: A Simple House</h2>

<p>Another example using only rectangles — notice how <em>draw order</em> matters for the windows and door (they need to be drawn <em>after</em> the wall).</p>

<CanvasDemo
  id="house"
  title="House with Rectangles (and one triangle)"
  width={500}
  height={350}
  code={`
// Sky gradient (we'll fake it with rectangles)
var skyColors = ['#0a1628', '#0d2137', '#103050', '#1a4060', '#2a5a7a'];
for (var i = 0; i < skyColors.length; i++) {
  ctx.fillStyle = skyColors[i];
  ctx.fillRect(0, i * 50, 500, 50);
}

// Ground
ctx.fillStyle = '#1a3a1a';
ctx.fillRect(0, 250, 500, 100);

// Grass detail
ctx.fillStyle = '#2a5a2a';
ctx.fillRect(0, 250, 500, 8);

// House wall
ctx.fillStyle = '#8b6914';
ctx.fillRect(120, 130, 200, 120);

// Roof (we'll use a filled triangle — a path, sneak preview!)
ctx.beginPath();
ctx.moveTo(100, 130);    // left edge
ctx.lineTo(220, 50);     // peak
ctx.lineTo(340, 130);    // right edge
ctx.closePath();
ctx.fillStyle = '#c0392b';
ctx.fill();

// Door
ctx.fillStyle = '#5d3a1a';
ctx.fillRect(195, 180, 40, 70);
// Doorknob
ctx.fillStyle = '#d29922';
ctx.fillRect(225, 218, 6, 6);

// Windows
ctx.fillStyle = '#d29922';
ctx.fillRect(140, 160, 35, 35);  // left window
ctx.fillRect(265, 160, 35, 35);  // right window

// Window cross-bars
ctx.fillStyle = '#5d3a1a';
ctx.fillRect(140, 175, 35, 3);   // left horizontal
ctx.fillRect(155, 160, 3, 35);   // left vertical
ctx.fillRect(265, 175, 35, 3);   // right horizontal
ctx.fillRect(280, 160, 3, 35);   // right vertical

// Chimney
ctx.fillStyle = '#7a3a1a';
ctx.fillRect(280, 60, 30, 70);

// Moon
ctx.beginPath();
ctx.arc(420, 60, 25, 0, Math.PI * 2);
ctx.fillStyle = '#e6edf3';
ctx.fill();

// Stars
ctx.fillStyle = '#e6edf3';
var stars = [[50,30],[100,70],[350,40],[300,20],[450,90],[80,120],[400,130]];
stars.forEach(function(s) {
  ctx.fillRect(s[0], s[1], 2, 2);
});
  `}
/>

<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->
<!-- SECTION 8 — Nightscape combo                 -->
<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->

<h2>Putting It All Together: Night Cityscape</h2>

<p>Here's a more complex scene showing how many simple rectangles combine into something impressive. Study the code — it's all <code>fillRect</code>, <code>strokeRect</code>, and <code>clearRect</code>!</p>

<CanvasDemo
  id="cityscape"
  title="Night Cityscape — Only Rectangles!"
  width={500}
  height={350}
  code={`
// Sky
ctx.fillStyle = '#0d1117';
ctx.fillRect(0, 0, 500, 350);

// Ground
ctx.fillStyle = '#1a3a1a';
ctx.fillRect(0, 260, 500, 90);

// Road
ctx.fillStyle = '#21262d';
ctx.fillRect(0, 280, 500, 70);
// Road lines
ctx.fillStyle = '#d29922';
for (var i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
  ctx.fillRect(10 + i * 52, 312, 30, 4);
}

// Building 1 (tall, left)
ctx.fillStyle = '#161b22';
ctx.fillRect(20, 80, 80, 180);
ctx.fillStyle = '#d29922';
for (var row = 0; row < 6; row++) {
  for (var col = 0; col < 2; col++) {
    if (Math.random() > 0.3) {
      ctx.fillStyle = Math.random() > 0.5 ? '#d29922' : '#58a6ff';
      ctx.fillRect(32 + col * 35, 95 + row * 27, 18, 18);
    }
  }
}

// Building 2 (medium, center-left)
ctx.fillStyle = '#21262d';
ctx.fillRect(120, 140, 100, 120);
ctx.fillStyle = '#58a6ff';
for (var row = 0; row < 3; row++) {
  for (var col = 0; col < 3; col++) {
    if (Math.random() > 0.25) {
      ctx.fillRect(132 + col * 30, 155 + row * 35, 18, 22);
    }
  }
}

// Building 3 (wide, center)
ctx.fillStyle = '#30363d';
ctx.fillRect(240, 170, 120, 90);
for (var row = 0; row < 2; row++) {
  for (var col = 0; col < 4; col++) {
    ctx.fillStyle = Math.random() > 0.4 ? '#d29922' : '#161b22';
    ctx.fillRect(250 + col * 28, 182 + row * 35, 18, 22);
  }
}

// Building 4 (tallest, right)
ctx.fillStyle = '#161b22';
ctx.fillRect(380, 50, 90, 210);
// Antenna
ctx.fillStyle = '#f85149';
ctx.fillRect(420, 30, 6, 20);
ctx.fillStyle = '#8b949e';
ctx.fillRect(423, 20, 1, 10);
for (var row = 0; row < 7; row++) {
  for (var col = 0; col < 3; col++) {
    if (Math.random() > 0.2) {
      ctx.fillStyle = Math.random() > 0.6 ? '#58a6ff' : '#d29922';
      ctx.fillRect(392 + col * 25, 62 + row * 27, 15, 18);
    }
  }
}

// Moon
ctx.fillStyle = '#e6edf3';
ctx.beginPath();
ctx.arc(450, 45, 20, 0, Math.PI * 2);
ctx.fill();
// Crescent effect
ctx.fillStyle = '#0d1117';
ctx.beginPath();
ctx.arc(460, 38, 18, 0, Math.PI * 2);
ctx.fill();

// Stars
ctx.fillStyle = '#e6edf3';
for (var i = 0; i < 20; i++) {
  var sx = Math.random() * 500;
  var sy = Math.random() * 60;
  ctx.fillRect(sx, sy, 1.5, 1.5);
}
  `}
/>

<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->
<!-- SECTION 9 — Challenges                       -->
<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->

<h2>Challenges</h2>

<p>Try these exercises to practice what you've learned. You can open your browser's console (F12) and create your own canvas, or modify the demo code above by looking at the patterns.</p>

<div class="concept">
  <p><strong>Challenge 1: Traffic Light</strong></p>
  <pre style="color: var(--accent); font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.4;">
    Draw a traffic light:
    - A tall dark rectangle for the housing
    - Three circles (red, yellow, green) stacked vertically
    - A pole (thin rectangle) below

    Hint: You know fillRect for the housing and pole.
    For circles, use:
      ctx.beginPath();
      ctx.arc(x, y, radius, 0, Math.PI * 2);
      ctx.fill();
    (We'll cover arcs fully in Lesson 2!)
  </pre>
</div>

<div class="concept">
  <p><strong>Challenge 2: Checkerboard</strong></p>
  <pre style="color: var(--accent); font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.4;">{`    Draw an 8x8 checkerboard pattern:
    - Use a nested for loop (row and column)
    - Alternate colors based on (row + col) % 2
    - Each square should be 40x40 pixels

    Hint:
      for (var row = 0; row < 8; row++) {
        for (var col = 0; col < 8; col++) {
          if ((row + col) % 2 === 0) {
            ctx.fillStyle = '#e6edf3';
          } else {
            ctx.fillStyle = '#30363d';
          }
          ctx.fillRect(col * 40, row * 40, 40, 40);
        }
      }`}</pre>
</div>

<div class="concept">
  <p><strong>Challenge 3: Bar Chart</strong></p>
  <pre style="color: var(--accent); font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.4;">
    Draw a bar chart from an array of data:
      var data = [80, 150, 60, 200, 120];

    - Each bar is 50px wide with 20px gaps
    - Bar height = the data value
    - Bars grow UP from the bottom (y = canvasHeight - value)
    - Different color for each bar
    - Labels underneath each bar

    This is a common real-world use of Canvas!
  </pre>
</div>

<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->
<!-- Summary                                       -->
<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->

<div class="concept">
  <p><strong>What you learned in this lesson:</strong></p>
  <pre style="color: var(--accent); font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.4;">
    Concept              How to do it
    ──────────────────── ───────────────────────────────
    Get drawing context  ctx = canvas.getContext('2d')
    Set fill color       ctx.fillStyle = '#ff0000'
    Set stroke color     ctx.strokeStyle = '#00ff00'
    Fill a rectangle     ctx.fillRect(x, y, w, h)
    Outline a rectangle  ctx.strokeRect(x, y, w, h)
    Erase an area        ctx.clearRect(x, y, w, h)
    Set line thickness   ctx.lineWidth = 5
    Make dashed lines    ctx.setLineDash([dash, gap])

    Key ideas:
    - (0,0) is top-left. Y goes DOWN.
    - Canvas size != CSS size. Use HTML attributes.
    - Later draws cover earlier draws (painter's algorithm).
    - fillStyle/strokeStyle persist until you change them.
  </pre>
</div>

</LessonLayout>
